cat << 'EOF'

================================================================================
SOLUTION: Use Transaction Pooler Connection String
================================================================================

The Direct Connection now requires IPv6, which is why Python cannot connect.

STEPS:
1. In the Supabase screenshot you showed, click the "Method" dropdown
2. Select "Transaction pooler" instead of "Direct connection"
3. Copy the new connection string that appears (it will use port 6543)
4. Update your .env file with that connection string

The Transaction pooler connection string will look like:
postgresql://postgres.mjsxwzpxzalhgkekseyo:[PASSWORD]@aws-0-us-east-1.pooler.supabase.com:6543/postgres

This will work over IPv4 and is actually recommended for production anyway!

================================================================================

EOF
cd /Users/amelton/mentions/mentions_backend && python3 -c "from core.config import settings; import re; conn = settings.DB_CONN; masked = re.sub(r'://([^:]+):([^@]+)@', r'://\1:****@', conn); print('Current DB_CONN:', masked); print('Port:', conn.split(':')[-1].split('/')[0] if ':' in conn else 'unknown')"
cd /Users/amelton/mentions/mentions_backend && grep "^DB_CONN=" .env | head -1
cd /Users/amelton/mentions/mentions_backend && env | grep DB_CONN
cd /Users/amelton/mentions/mentions_backend && python test_env_loading.py
cd /Users/amelton/mentions/mentions_backend && grep "^DB_CONN=" .env
